WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.480
Hello everybody, I know it's like afternoon lull, end of a session, so thank you all for

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:08.160
being here for topics that I think are really important.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:12.080
So extra credit to people in this room, a lot of cool stuff happening at this conference,

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:17.719
but I think the question of, you know, how do we keep this awesome thing that we have

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:19.680
rolling is a huge question.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:25.600
So my talk today is about, you know, sustainable open-source ecosystems and specifically thinking

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:29.879
kind of from the perspective that is personal for me about a grant that I'm on right now

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:37.000
as well as the famous rstats hashtag on the website formerly known as Twitter and elsewhere.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.720
And so I'm a professor of statistics at Cal Poly, but perhaps that is not maybe the credential

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:44.720
that matters today.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:48.560
The credential that matters in this talk is that I am an R groupie, and that all I do

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:53.520
is follow R around to all the conferences and go to the talks and like act very excited.

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:58.639
So that's maybe why I'm here giving this talk.

00:00:58.639 --> 00:01:03.119
So basically over the past four years, a few things have happened that have made me

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:07.800
really think about, like, what is the future and sustainability of R?

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:13.160
One of them is obviously a global pandemic, which I've chosen to represent by RStudio

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:17.760
Conf, Posit Conf going online, rather than one of the depressing pictures we keep seeing

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:23.440
in the news, but obviously that sort of changed a lot of people's relationship, I suppose,

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.879
with their work and with R.

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:30.919
And then the next thing that happened was Posit rebranding to Posit, and I think we

00:01:30.919 --> 00:01:35.800
all as R folks had a lot of questions about, you know, what is kind of R's role in this

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:39.839
world where Python is also very important and other languages too, of course, and our

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:42.559
sort of fearless leaders, RStudio, don't have R in the name.

00:01:42.559 --> 00:01:44.919
What does that mean?

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:51.519
And then stuff happened on Twitter, namely it becoming kind of inhospitable to big parts

00:01:51.519 --> 00:01:55.739
of our community, and so a lot of the community left because they didn't want to be in a place

00:01:55.739 --> 00:01:59.059
where some of the valued members of our community didn't feel safe.

00:01:59.059 --> 00:02:00.540
So this was a big blow, right?

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:05.059
I hate to say how much of my career depended on Twitter, but it was really where we were

00:02:05.059 --> 00:02:10.860
connecting and sharing things about R and having those conversations, and it's not really

00:02:10.860 --> 00:02:11.860
that anymore.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:13.300
There's not just one place anymore.

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:19.220
But then a good thing happened last year for me and for everybody and for R, which is that

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:26.339
the NSF released this new program, POSE, which is Pathways to Open Source Ecosystems,

00:02:26.339 --> 00:02:31.460
and they're basically supporting kind of not the code part of open source, but the building

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:36.699
of the infrastructure that is necessary to keep important open source projects alive.

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:41.539
And so my friend Toby Hawking, my now friend, I only knew him from Twitter, is at Northern

00:02:41.539 --> 00:02:47.020
Arizona University, or he actually just moved from there, but he got this grant to reinvigorate

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:48.899
the data.table package.

00:02:48.899 --> 00:02:53.020
The people here that use data.table, if you're aware of data.table, it's one of these packages

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:57.380
that has a cult following, a large cult following, it's not niche, but the people that use it

00:02:57.380 --> 00:03:01.600
really use it, really love it, and it was pretty much built and maintained largely by

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:05.500
one person, and he burned out a little bit, and so it kind of got a little stagnant.

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:10.399
So Toby brought me in on this grant because I am very much a tidyverse person, but I do

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:12.179
love data.table.

00:03:12.179 --> 00:03:16.339
I think it's kind of a both, not, or sort of situation.

00:03:16.339 --> 00:03:22.779
So I've been thinking about how to make data.table specifically more sustainable on this grant.

00:03:22.779 --> 00:03:26.500
So as these things are happening, as I've been thinking about it, I kind of am thinking

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.699
about three questions here.

00:03:28.699 --> 00:03:33.500
Versus R itself, like what keeps R, you know, relevant, popular, why is it that R is still

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:36.139
growing even though Python is growing exponentially?

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:39.440
You know, those are not mutually exclusive.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:43.740
And then packages, like data.table, specifically what keeps these packages sustainable and current?

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:46.699
You know, we just heard about the challenges involved, right, in keeping packages fresh

00:03:46.699 --> 00:03:47.699
and available.

00:03:47.699 --> 00:03:52.779
And the community, right, what keeps us engaged, or where are we engaged, and how are we connected

00:03:52.779 --> 00:03:53.779
to each other?

00:03:53.779 --> 00:03:58.259
And so I think, you know, the answer to these three questions is, like, the people in this

00:03:58.259 --> 00:03:59.259
room.

00:03:59.259 --> 00:04:03.220
Specifically, the people in this room, in that room, on the internet, you know, it's

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:04.220
us.

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:10.339
And as I've been thinking about this talk and, like, who's my target audience, I'm thinking,

00:04:10.339 --> 00:04:16.380
you know, it's not the big-time developers and the full-time positive employees, sorry.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.820
And it's not really beginners, people that are new to R. If you're here learning things

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:23.140
for the first time, you know, your only job is to learn and grow.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:26.619
This is for the people in between, which is most of us here.

00:04:26.619 --> 00:04:29.739
Like those of us that are really benefiting from these tools, that are using them heavily,

00:04:29.739 --> 00:04:33.420
but maybe aren't quite, you know, the Hadley Wickhams of the world.

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:38.980
And so what I realized, putting this talk together, is that I'm speaking to myself.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:42.140
I'm thinking about, you know, these are the things, like, the kind of post-pandemic I

00:04:42.140 --> 00:04:46.299
now have, like, elevated maybe from beginner to not beginner around that time.

00:04:46.299 --> 00:04:49.459
And these are the things I need to be doing better.

00:04:49.459 --> 00:04:52.940
Like I have been behaving like a beginner and just accepting the gifts of the R community

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:54.420
and not giving back.

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:58.519
So think of all these things that I am telling you to do here as things that I'm also telling

00:04:58.519 --> 00:05:04.019
myself to do and kind of pledging that I want to be better at going forward.

00:05:04.019 --> 00:05:07.100
So let's think first about creation and maintenance of software.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:09.380
That dovetails nicely off that last talk.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:12.820
You know, what do we need to do to support this, even if we're not the ones building

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:14.980
maybe the big packages?

00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:18.899
The first thing you can give to developers, the big developers, is your time.

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:24.220
Yes, contributing code, as you heard from Heather, is very nice, but, like, there are

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:26.459
other things you can do, right?

00:05:26.459 --> 00:05:31.420
Filing issues with feature requests, bug reports, all that good stuff, primarily on GitHub is

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:33.059
where you would do this.

00:05:33.059 --> 00:05:34.320
Translation.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.040
There's a big translation project in this data table grant.

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:41.279
So if you speak a language that is not well represented in R, would love if you reach

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:42.279
out.

00:05:42.279 --> 00:05:45.320
We have funding for translation projects.

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.239
Fixing typos, like little things that you find.

00:05:47.239 --> 00:05:50.320
My students sometimes find things and they get really excited when they can actually

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:54.500
contribute, even though they're brand new, they found a typo.

00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:58.000
And then I'm going to kind of beat this over the head today.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.079
Blogging and posting is so valuable.

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:04.119
Like if you use a package and it solves a problem for you, mention it.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:07.279
And then the developer of that package will be so happy, I promise you.

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:13.600
That is one of the best things you can do for the developers of this software.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:16.359
And I thought that this was maybe, like, annoying, right?

00:06:16.359 --> 00:06:19.480
To be, like, filing issues or bothering developers of packages.

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:24.000
But the more I talk to these developers, the more I understand they want this.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:25.359
They want the feature requests.

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:29.119
Even if they have to say no to it, even if they can't do it, they want those suggestions.

00:06:29.119 --> 00:06:31.959
They want the bug reports so they know what's going on.

00:06:31.959 --> 00:06:35.239
These are very valuable.

00:06:35.239 --> 00:06:37.600
The next thing you can give your developers is credit.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:41.440
And I've been sort of bringing this to all the academic conferences, especially, where

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.239
they're writing papers.

00:06:43.239 --> 00:06:47.839
If you have a project, whether it is a formal paper or a blog post or, you know, just an

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:51.519
analysis project, cite your packages.

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:52.519
All of them.

00:06:52.519 --> 00:06:53.519
I mean it.

00:06:53.519 --> 00:06:54.519
All of them.

00:06:54.519 --> 00:06:57.619
Like, if you use some package to make your font prettier on ggplot, that was work that

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:01.239
someone did to make that software so that you can do that thing, right?

00:07:01.239 --> 00:07:03.920
And you should be giving them credit, at least in some way, at least acknowledging

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:05.519
that you used it.

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:09.640
Maybe not a formal citation like in a paper, but a list of packages that you used or mentioning

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:10.640
it in your blog.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:14.920
But if you are writing formal papers of any kind, there's no excuse, because here are

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:19.359
three lines of code that will just get you copy-paste bib text citations for every single

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:21.679
package that that project depends on.

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:22.679
So no excuse.

00:07:22.679 --> 00:07:23.679
There it is.

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:24.679
Gift to you.

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:25.679
And to me.

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:29.959
And then, of course, Heather also mentioned money.

00:07:29.959 --> 00:07:34.079
We unfortunately live in a society and it happens to be a capitalist society where people

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:35.079
need to buy food.

00:07:35.079 --> 00:07:38.679
So these developers are doing things out of the goodness of their heart.

00:07:38.679 --> 00:07:40.679
But you can help out.

00:07:40.679 --> 00:07:44.440
And I think open source is cool because you get to use the product before you decide if

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:46.399
you want to buy the product, you know?

00:07:46.399 --> 00:07:49.239
No one's asking you to kind of give up front.

00:07:49.239 --> 00:07:53.559
But if you see one of these like GitHub donation, people have them on their personal GitHub

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:54.559
sites.

00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:59.200
If you see a buy me a coffee button below a particularly nice app or analysis, if you

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:03.519
have used and appreciated that thing, hit that button, even a little bit.

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:07.640
Both the gesture means a lot and, of course, the dollars mean things to people.

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:14.279
And if you do have access to kind of company funds of any kind, please fund workshops and

00:08:14.279 --> 00:08:15.420
professional development.

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:18.079
It's really hard to adopt these new tools, right?

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:21.959
So the more that private companies can fund them, the more they will have people in the

00:08:21.959 --> 00:08:24.239
workspace that can do these things.

00:08:24.239 --> 00:08:29.559
Or at least, you know, support your employees to do things like this.

00:08:29.559 --> 00:08:32.200
If you're giving your employees at least a little bit of creative time, a lot of the

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:37.000
greatest like open source work of our time has come from people at private for profit

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:42.039
companies who are allowed to use a bit of their time creating these open source tools.

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:45.080
So I think that goes a long way.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:48.580
And then I'm glad Heather covered this in much more detail, but there are these foundations

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:52.520
out there that are kind of clearing houses where you can donate larger sums of money.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:56.719
And then these organizations, these nonprofit organizations, help distribute it to projects

00:08:56.719 --> 00:08:59.520
that are going to help grow our ecosystem.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:02.440
So really appreciate all the existence.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:08.799
These are the ones I know, but there's many more out there.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:12.919
And then just a word because those of us kind of in this middle zone, we do sometimes develop.

00:09:12.919 --> 00:09:17.640
I have kind of like one and a half packages that I need to work on.

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:18.640
Make it easy to support you.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:24.200
Don't think that this financial support or emotional moral support is only deserved by

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:25.960
the people making the massive packages.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:28.679
Like if you've made something, make it easy to help you.

00:09:28.679 --> 00:09:34.239
So add a citation file if you want the citation to be in any way non-standard.

00:09:34.239 --> 00:09:38.559
The kind of default from that code I showed you is just like the info from the description

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:40.400
file of the package.

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:45.479
But you can set it up so that instead it points to like if you have a paper, maybe in a

00:09:45.479 --> 00:09:50.799
journal that's related, or if you just want that citation to be different, add that in.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:53.159
If you're a big project, maybe join one of these foundations.

00:09:53.159 --> 00:09:56.119
We're working on this for data.table.

00:09:56.119 --> 00:10:00.000
If you're a small project, I think our universe and our OpenSAC are a good place to go just

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.320
to get your package kind of part of a larger ecosystem.

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:07.559
Not so much for funding, but for, you know, the other types of support and also letting

00:10:07.559 --> 00:10:11.280
people know about your package.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:14.119
And you know, if you if you were kind of in that position where you're like, I really

00:10:14.119 --> 00:10:17.919
want to do this thing, but I'm not motivated or I don't have time or I just can't make

00:10:17.919 --> 00:10:18.919
it happen.

00:10:18.919 --> 00:10:22.479
I do think these little like donation buttons, you know, put them out there.

00:10:22.479 --> 00:10:24.039
There's no harm in putting them out there.

00:10:24.039 --> 00:10:27.760
And if someone appreciates what you did or wants you to do more, they might click it.

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:30.880
So get those set up.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:34.559
And another really important thing I want to mention if you're on any kind of development

00:10:34.559 --> 00:10:40.119
project is this idea of a governance document, contributor guide, and code of conduct.

00:10:40.119 --> 00:10:44.200
The contributor guide is going to make it easier for people to help be part of that

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:45.200
development.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:48.039
Most of us don't live in a silo and we could use that help.

00:10:48.039 --> 00:10:52.440
Code of conduct is a good way to keep your community, you know, feel like a safe place

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:53.679
for the whole community.

00:10:53.679 --> 00:10:56.280
And this governance document has been very powerful.

00:10:56.280 --> 00:11:00.359
So this data.table project has a new governance document.

00:11:00.359 --> 00:11:05.640
It started as a GitHub issue discussion that looks like this.

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.440
proposal, structure, discussion between the contributors.

00:11:10.440 --> 00:11:11.799
And like none of this is official, right?

00:11:11.799 --> 00:11:12.799
There's no boss.

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:15.799
There's Toby who has the grant, but he's not the boss.

00:11:15.799 --> 00:11:19.840
There's a lot of contributors to data.table, including the creator, Matt Dowell.

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:22.000
And this was just a community discussion.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.239
So you don't have to be like a big fancy organization to have a governance document that sort of

00:11:27.239 --> 00:11:32.039
says whose responsibility is what in the maintenance of this project.

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:37.599
And then they did this poll request, you know, where the actual thing, the other one,

00:11:37.599 --> 00:11:39.640
you know, drafts of it were added.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:40.960
This was all happening on GitHub, right?

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:41.960
But it was a real conversation.

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:46.119
And I just think that's really, really cool and powerful.

00:11:46.119 --> 00:11:48.359
And then it was approved.

00:11:48.359 --> 00:11:50.679
You can see which date it was approved.

00:11:50.679 --> 00:11:53.239
It was in December of 2023 here.

00:11:53.239 --> 00:11:56.000
And this is the activity on the data.table repository.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:02.599
So you can see that kind of drought between, you know, I guess it's more like 2021 and present.

00:12:02.599 --> 00:12:06.679
And then there was the first major release of data.table in four years, right after this

00:12:06.679 --> 00:12:08.359
governance document was approved.

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:11.000
Because everyone understood whose responsibility is it to review the code?

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.640
Whose responsibility is it to, you know, do the release?

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:19.880
All that good stuff really drove the project forward.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:21.320
Next question in the room.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:22.719
How do we help people learn?

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:24.159
This has a fairly easy answer.

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:25.440
Please support education.

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:29.960
I know sometimes it can feel like a big university asking for help is like this.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.760
But we really don't have, I'm a professor at a public university, we don't have that

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:37.679
many resources for things like adopting and learning new tools.

00:12:37.679 --> 00:12:40.719
So the more that you can put out there, the better it is.

00:12:40.719 --> 00:12:43.320
Like my students are finding the stuff you're putting out in the world.

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:46.359
I promise they're using it if you put it out there.

00:12:46.359 --> 00:12:49.280
And I also think people are like, well, I'm not an expert in that thing.

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:53.320
But a resource made by someone actively learning the thing about how they are learning it,

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.960
like a blog post, is a lot more valuable than like the expert perspective,

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:58.840
trying to boil it down to first principles.

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:01.760
So your stuff is helping our students.

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:06.919
And then just, you know, the free access to tools, that is really important, too.

00:13:06.919 --> 00:13:09.840
I'm really grateful to Posit that makes a lot of their tools.

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:12.640
This is a secret they probably don't want me to tell, but they often will make their

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:17.039
professional tools available for educators if you're using it in the classroom only.

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:18.520
And that's really appreciated.

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:24.119
And a lot of people are kind of hesitant to do this blogging thing just because, you know,

00:13:24.119 --> 00:13:25.119
oh, well, this is me.

00:13:25.119 --> 00:13:26.520
It was me to me again.

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:31.719
I have so many half-finished blog posts, and I'm like, it's not perfect, I can't post it.

00:13:31.719 --> 00:13:33.119
I want us to get away from that.

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:36.919
Like, I really think we should get back to this world that we kind of had in Twitter,

00:13:36.919 --> 00:13:40.719
where you are just spamming your every idea and every new thing you learn.

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:42.119
That was so fun, right?

00:13:42.119 --> 00:13:44.520
And it didn't have to be perfect, and it didn't have to be polished.

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:45.919
I want more mini blogs.

00:13:46.119 --> 00:13:47.520
I want more mini blogs.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:52.119
I want to hear, like, tonight, what you thought was cool today, what you learned at this conference,

00:13:52.119 --> 00:13:54.919
because I use those things.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:13:59.119
So, a push towards short, imperfect blog posts, nothing against the beautiful, you know,

00:13:59.119 --> 00:14:03.719
Next Great American Novel style ones, but let's get more out there.

00:14:03.719 --> 00:14:06.520
